https://github.com/calcom/cal.com/pull/1:
parseRefreshTokenResponse defines an invalid Zod schema using computed keys like `[z.string().toString()]`, which will create a literal key (e.g. "[object Object]") rather than a catch-all/index signature. This means the schema will not validate real token responses as intended.

Evidence (packages/app-store/_utils/oauth/parseRefreshTokenResponse.ts):
```ts
const minimumTokenResponseSchema = z.object({
  access_token: z.string(),
  //   Assume that any property with a number is the expiry
  [z.string().toString()]: z.number(),
  //   Allow other properties in the token response
  [z.string().optional().toString()]: z.unknown().optional(),
});
```

refreshOAuthTokens returns a raw fetch `Response` when sync is enabled, but multiple call sites treat the return value as a provider token object / axios response (accessing `.data` or token fields). This will break at runtime under sync mode.

Evidence (packages/app-store/_utils/oauth/refreshOAuthTokens.ts):
```ts
if (APP_CREDENTIAL_SHARING_ENABLED && process.env.CALCOM_CREDENTIAL_SYNC_ENDPOINT && userId) {
  const response = await fetch(process.env.CALCOM_CREDENTIAL_SYNC_ENDPOINT, { ... });
  return response; // Response
}
```
Call site examples:
- Hubspot expects `HubspotToken` (packages/app-store/hubspot/lib/CalendarService.ts):
```ts
const hubspotRefreshToken: HubspotToken = await refreshOAuthTokens(...);
```
- Zoho CRM expects axios response with `.data` (packages/app-store/zohocrm/lib/CalendarService.ts):
```ts
const zohoCrmTokenInfo = await refreshOAuthTokens(...);
if (!zohoCrmTokenInfo.data.error) {
```
- Google expects `res.data` (packages/app-store/googlecalendar/lib/CalendarService.ts):
```ts
const res = await refreshOAuthTokens(...);
const token = res?.data;
```

Zoho Bigin CalendarService passes `credentialId` (credential record id) as the `userId` argument to refreshOAuthTokens. refreshOAuthTokens uses this value as `calcomUserId`, so the sync endpoint will receive the wrong identifier.

Evidence (packages/app-store/zoho-bigin/lib/CalendarService.ts):
```ts
const credentialId = credential.id;
...
const tokenInfo = await refreshOAuthTokens(
  async () => await axios.post(...),
  "zoho-bigin",
  credentialId
);
```
And refreshOAuthTokens uses it as:
```ts
body: new URLSearchParams({
  calcomUserId: userId.toString(),
  appSlug,
}),
```

SalesforceCalendarService misuses parseRefreshTokenResponse: it expects a safeParse-like result with `.success`/`.data`, but parseRefreshTokenResponse throws on failure and returns the safeParse result object. The code then checks `.success` (dead/unreachable on failure) and proceeds, indicating a contract mismatch that will cause incorrect control flow.

Evidence:
- parseRefreshTokenResponse throws on failure (packages/app-store/_utils/oauth/parseRefreshTokenResponse.ts):
```ts
if (!refreshTokenResponse.success) {
  throw new Error("Invalid refreshed tokens were returned");
}
return refreshTokenResponse;
```
- Salesforce checks `.success` after calling it (packages/app-store/salesforce/lib/CalendarService.ts):
```ts
const accessTokenParsed = parseRefreshTokenResponse(accessTokenJson, salesforceTokenSchema);

if (!accessTokenParsed.success) {
  return Promise.reject(new Error("Invalid refreshed tokens were returned"));
}
```

